{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781418909,"nonce":"s720LdL22xmYoxccwYtAlURht5w=","title":"squealy has no column type for timestamps. `std::time::SystemTime` (and `time` / `chrono` types) don't implement `HasColumnType`, so date/time columns can't be declared idiomatically.","message":"```rust\ncreated_at: C::Type\u003c'scope, std::time::SystemTime\u003e,\n```\n\n```\nerror[E0277]: the trait bound `SystemTime: HasColumnType` is not satisfied\n  = help: the following other types implement trait `HasColumnType`:\n          bool, f32, f64, i128, i16, i32, i64, i8, and 8 others\n```\n\n\nStore timestamps as `i64` epoch seconds (`bigint`), converting at the boundary. Works, but loses native `timestamptz` semantics (timezone, range queries, DB-side `now()`/comparisons, tooling).\n\n\nA timestamp column type behind the relevant feature — e.g. `HasColumnType` + `Encode` / `Decode\u003cPostgres\u003e` for `std::time::SystemTime` (tokio-postgres maps `SystemTime` \u003c-\u003e `timestamptz` natively via `with-time`/built-in), and/or `time::OffsetDateTime` / `chrono::DateTime\u003cUtc\u003e` under `time` / `chrono` features (mirroring how `uuid` and `serde`/`Json` are gated).\n\n\ngitana catalog timestamps: `created_at`, `deleted_at`, `expires_at`, `last_used_at`. Worked around with `bigint` epoch; a \"nice to have\" for an idiomatic schema, not a blocker.","files":null}]}